The paper deals with game theory and algorithmic social cost minimization, which are core topics in computer science. The use of potential games and strict cost-sharing schemes suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.GT (Game Theory) sub-category. The mention of Bayes-Nash equilibrium and incomplete information suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The use of algorithms and approximation factors suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The focus on social cost minimization suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. Finally, the mention of Bayesian network design models suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category.
